`crates/ctx-scan/tests` is the executable spec for `ctx-scan`'s CLI-facing behaviors — walking, hashing, summarizing, staleness-checking, orphan reconciliation, and the Stop-hook — as they interact with real and fake filesystems. Depending on this crate's public API is validated against these tests; changing `runner`/`walker`/`Fs`/`Agent` signatures requires updating all three files in lockstep, since each imports `ctx_summarize`'s traits and `runner::MAX_TARGETS`/`load_prompts` directly.

All three files share a two-harness pattern: hermetic tests use in-memory `FakeFs` + a call-counting agent stub (`RecordingAgent`/`StubAgent`) to assert exact agent-call counts and no-model operations; real-fs tests use per-test tmpdirs under the OS temp dir (`test_dir(label)`) with manual cleanup before and after, and `prompts_path()` resolving real prompt files relative to `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` regardless of cwd. A change to either harness (e.g. `FakeFs`'s seeded prompt paths, or `test_dir`'s naming/cleanup) affects all three files.

Cross-file invariants: staleness/orphan detection is split by mechanism — `scan.rs` covers hash-mismatch staleness and missing-artifact detection; `reconcile.rs` covers orphans from deleted/rescoped sources, with file-deletion caught via hash-diff and directory-deletion caught only by directory-tree reconciliation. `stop_hook.rs` builds on both: it asserts the hook is read-only and never itself calls `update_run`, deferring regeneration entirely to the pipeline tested in `scan.rs`. `update_run`'s incremental behavior (regenerate only touched leaf + ancestors, prune orphans with zero agent calls when otherwise fresh) is asserted in `scan.rs` and relied on implicitly by `reconcile.rs` and `stop_hook.rs`'s "make fresh" setup step.